                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100213">Fulda</placeName>
                                </origPlace>,<origDate notAfter="0850" notBefore="0801"> 9th century, first half.</origDate>
                            </p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The manuscript was kept in the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100154">abbey of Saint-Denis</orgName>, Paris, from an early date, but was written in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100213">Fulda</placeName> according to <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107187">Lehmann (1934)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="167" to="167" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>It was acquired by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100086"> Queen Christina</persName> from <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102544"> Paul Petau’s</persName> collection (See <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107189">Meyier (1947)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="115" to="115" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>) and brought to Sweden, where it remained after her abdication. First mentioned in Vossius’s catalogue of 1651 (U 202:1). There are 3 signa on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>: The older signum, <quote>No 28,</quote> is found in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e) and <quote>e. 30.3.15</quote> is found in Hammarsköld’s catalogue from the 19th century (U 133). <quote>A 137</quote> is the current signum.</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
